{{Infobox sportsperson | headercolor = lightblue | name = Judith Chacón | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = | fullname = Judith Andrea Chacón Ozuriaga | nickname = | nationality = {{VEN}} | residence = | birth_date = {{birth date|1986|1|29|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Caracas]], [[Capital District (Venezuela)|Distrito Capital]], Venezuela | death_date = {{death date and age|2009|10|27|1986|1|29|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Barquisimeto]], [[Lara, Venezuela]] | height = {{height|m=1.52|abbr=on}} | weight = {{convert|53|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} | website = | country = | sport = [[Olympic weightlifting|Weightlifting]] | event = 53 kg | collegeteam = | club = | team = | turnedpro = | coach = | retired = | coaching = | worlds = | regionals = | nationals = | olympics = | paralympics = | highestranking = | pb = | medaltemplates = }}
'''Judith Andrea Chacón Ozuriaga''' (January 29, 1986{{spaced ndash}}October 27, 2009) was a Venezuelan [[weightlifter]].<ref>{{cite sports-reference|Judith Chacón|https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ch/judith-chacon-1.html|25 December 2012}}</ref> Chacon represented [[Venezuela]] at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]], where she competed for the [[Weightlifting at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Women's 53 kg|women's featherweight category]] (53&nbsp;kg). Chacon placed last out of nine weightlifters in this event, as she successfully lifted 80&nbsp;kg in the single-motion [[snatch (weightlifting)|snatch]], and hoisted 101&nbsp;kg in the two-part, shoulder-to-overhead [[clean and jerk]], for a total of 181&nbsp;kg. Her performance in weightlifting was also a top finish for Venezuela at these games.<ref>{{cite news|title=Women's 53kg (117 lbs)|url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/weightlifting/resultsandschedules/rsc=WLW053000/standings.html|publisher=[[NBC Olympics]]|accessdate=25 December 2012}}</ref> Shortly after the Olympics, she had briefly retired from weightlifting because of pregnancy.
On October 27, 2009, Chacon died from pregnancy-related complications, including the [[Influenza A virus subtype H1N1|H1N1 flu virus]] in her birthplace [[Caracas]]. According to Eddy Suarez, president of Venezuelan Weightlifting Federation, he regretted the sudden demise of Chacon, who would have been admitted to the hospital immediately for further treatment and speedy recovery. Following her death, the doctors managed to save her daughter from infection, and placed her in a special care.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fallece pesista venezolana Judith Chacón|trans-title=Venezuelan weightlifter Judith Chacón dies|language=Spanish|url=http://www.eluniversal.com/2009/10/29/pesa_ava_fallece-pesista-vene_29A2969211.shtml|publisher=El Universal Venezuela|date=29 October 2009|accessdate=25 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Judith Chacón perdió la batalla contra la gripe|trans-title=Judith Chacon lost the battle against influenza|language=Spanish|url=http://www.entornointeligente.com/resumen/resumen.php?items=974431|publisher=Entorno Intelligente|date=6 November 2009|accessdate=25 December 2012}}</ref>
