'''Mir Yar-Ahmad Khuzani Isfahani''' ({{lang-fa|امیر یاراحمد خوزانی اصفهانی}}), better known by his honorific title of '''Najm-e Sani''' ("The Second Star") was a [[Persian people|Persian]]{{sfn|Mazzaoui|2002}} nobleman from the [[Khuzani family]], who was the third person to serve as the ''vakil'' (vicegerent) of the [[Safavid dynasty|Safavid Empire]].

== Biography ==
Najm was born during the 15th-century in [[Isfahan]], and belonged to a prominent family which could trace its existence in Isfahan back to the 1440s.{{sfn|Newman|2008|p=157}} He had a brother named [[Mahmud Beg Khuzani]]. In 1509/10, Najm succeeded [[Amir Najm al-Din Mas'ud Gilani]] in the ''vakil'' office, and later in 1512, he, along with the [[Timurid dynasty|Timurid]] prince [[Babur]] attacked the marauding [[Uzbeks]], who had although suffered a heavy defeat in 1510 by [[Ismail I|Shah Ismail I]], kept making incursions into the eastern Safavid province of [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]].{{sfn|Mazzaoui|2002}} It is disputed whether Najm led the attack without approval from Ismail I or not.{{sfn|Mazzaoui|2002}} After having crossed the [[Oxus River]], Najm seized [[Qarshi]], and had the city sacked and its inhabitants brutally massacred, which resulted in the death of over 1,500 men, and even children and women. A small [[Sayyid]] community was also massacred by the army of Najm,{{sfn|Mazzaoui|2002}} the prominent poet [[Maulana Binai]] being one of them.

Najm then attacked Ghazdewan, a town near [[Bukhara]], but was unable to capture the town. Babur then advised Najm to retreat to Qarshi in order to wait for reinforcements. Najm, however, declined, which resulted in the mutiny of several [[Qizilbash]] chieftains who had been with him during his campaign.{{sfn|Mazzaoui|2002}} On November, a [[Battle of Ghazdewan|battle ensured at Ghazdewan]] between the Uzbeks and what was left of the army of Najm, which resulted in his defeat and capture. He was shortly executed,{{sfn|Mazzaoui|2002}}{{sfn|Newman|2008|p=20}} and was succeeded by [[Abd al-Baqi Yazdi]] in the ''vakil'' office.{{sfn|Soucek|1982|pp=105-106}}

