{{about|the silent film actress|the member of Congress|Virginia Foxx}} {{Infobox person | name = Virginia Fox | image = Virginia Fox 1922.jpg | imagesize = | caption =Fox in 1922 | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|1902|04|02}} | birth_place = [[Wheeling, West Virginia]], U.S. | death_date = {{death date and age|1982|10|14|1902|04|02}} | death_place = [[Palm Springs, California]], U.S. | restingplace = Buried next to her husband in [[Westwood Village Memorial Park Cemetery]] | nationality = American | occupation = Actress | yearsactive = 1915–1929 | spouse = [[Darryl F. Zanuck]] (1924–1979) | children = 3, including [[Richard D. Zanuck|Richard Darryl Zanuck]] (1934–2012) }}
'''Virginia Fox Zanuck''' (April 2, 1902 – October 14, 1982) was an American [[actress]] who starred in many [[silent film]]s of the 1910s and 1920s.
==Life and career== Fox was born in Wheeling, West Virginia (though her grave erroneously lists Charleston, W.Va. as her place of birth), the daughter of Marie (née Oglseby) and Frederick Fox.<ref>{{cite book | title=The Zanucks of Hollywood: the dark legacy of an American dynasty | publisher=Crown Publishers | author=Harris, Marlys J. | year=1989 | isbn=9780517570203}}</ref>
While on vacation from boarding school, Fox traveled to visit a friend in Los Angeles. The two made a casual stop by the studio of [[Mack Sennett]], where she was hired on the spot and made a bathing beauty in the studio's films. Fox went on to star as leading lady in many of the early films of [[Buster Keaton]], including 1920's highly regarded "Neighbors."<ref>VIRGINIA F. ZANUCK, SILENT MOVIE STAR, Obituary, ''The New York Times'', Oct. 15, 1982, https://www.nytimes.com/1982/10/15/obituaries/virginia-f-zanuck-silent-movie-star.html</ref>
In 1924 she married [[film producer]] [[Darryl F. Zanuck]], with whom she had three children, Darrylin (1931–2015), Susan Marie (1935–1980), and [[Richard D. Zanuck|Richard Darryl]] (1934–2012). Fox retired from acting, but was known as a behind-the-scenes influence on her husband's business decisions. The couple separated in 1956 over the studio mogul's affairs with other women, though they were never legally divorced; but according to Zanuck biographers, she cared for him at their home from the time he became mentally incapacitated in the early 1970s until his death in 1979.{{cn|date=November 2018}} She was buried near Darryl Zanuck at the [[Westwood Village Memorial Park Cemetery]] in [[Westwood, Los Angeles]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1995/08/13/travel/rip-in-la.html ''The New York Times'']</ref>
Despite some Internet accounts to the contrary, Virginia Fox was not related to William Fox, whose name is preserved in the company 20th Century Fox, which Darryl Zanuck created and led for decades. William Fox founded Fox Studios, but had lost control of it by the time Zanuck acquired it and merged it into his own empire.{{cn|date=November 2018}} [[File:Virginia Fox Zanuck's tomb in Westwood Memorial Park.JPG|thumb|Virginia Fox Zanuck's tomb in Westwood Memorial Park, Westwood, Los Angeles, California]]
